      Everything is securities fraud
   =20
 =20
If you are a U.S. senator interested in foreign policy and concerned with t=
he world=E2=80=99s perception of Israel=E2=80=99s occupation of the Palesti=
nian territories, there is really only one thing you can do, which is write=
 a letter to the Securities and Exchange Commission raising some questions =
about securities fraud:GOP senators on the Banking, Housing, and Urban Affa=
irs Committee have demanded answers from the Securities and Exchange Commis=
sion (SEC) on whether the parent company of Ben & Jerry=E2=80=99s has viola=
ted SEC rules in its Israel boycott.=C2=A0In a December letter obtained exc=
lusively by FOX Business to SEC Chairman Gary Gensler, Republican Sens. Tho=
m Tillis, of North Carolina, John Kennedy, of Louisiana, and Tim Scott, of =
South Carolina, called for an investigation into statements made by Unileve=
r following the Israeli-Palestinian conflict in July 2021.=C2=A0On July 19,=
 2021, Ben & Jerry=E2=80=99s announced it would no longer sell its ice crea=
m in the "Occupied Palestinian Territory," referring to the West Bank and G=
aza Strip. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Unilever backed the move saying, "We also welcome=
 the fact that Ben & Jerry=E2=80=99s will stay in Israel," noted the lawmak=
ers in their letter."There is strong reason to believe that these July 19 s=
tatements were knowingly and recklessly false," the GOP senators wrote, ref=
erencing an Israeli law that prohibits targeted boycotts based on location.=
This is actually the second congressional letter to the SEC about Palestini=
an-ice-cream-sales-based securities fraud that we have covered around here;=
 back in November I  wrote about a congressman who wants Unilever to update=
 its risk factors, and now these guys want Unilever investigated for its pr=
evious statements.=C2=A0Do you think that they are worried about Unilever=
=E2=80=99s shareholders? About them being deceived? About Unilever doing a =
clever fraud on those shareholders to induce them to buy Unilever stock by =
concealing the fact that its Ben & Jerry=E2=80=99s subsidiary=C2=A0won=E2=
=80=99t=C2=A0in fact be able to continue to sell ice cream in the non-Pales=
tinian parts of Israel?=C2=A0Come on.The point here is that =E2=80=9Ceveryt=
hing is securities fraud=E2=80=9D is a way to=C2=A0punish political speech.=
=C2=A0In general, in the U.S., people =E2=80=94=C2=A0and also corporations =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0are allowed to express their opinions about controversial po=
litical topics, and it is viewed as unseemly for the government to punish t=
hem for doing so. And this is true even if they are factually mistaken, or =
outright lying: It is bad=C2=A0for people to lie about political matters, b=
ut the punishment for that is pretty much =E2=80=9Cjournalists might call y=
ou a liar=E2=80=9D; the government is not in the business of punishing even=
 dishonest political speech.On the other hand it is illegal =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
it is securities fraud =E2=80=94=C2=A0for a company to lie to its sharehold=
ers to get them to buy stock, and that rule is generally interpreted broadl=
y enough that  essentially any untrue statement that a public company makes=
 can be called securities fraud.=C2=A0So you just combine those two things =
and you can turn any sort of political speech or position-taking by a publi=
c corporation (or its executives, or its subsidiaries) into securities frau=
d. Find some debatable premise in what they say: fraud. Or, failing that, y=
ou can accuse them of fraud for failing to include a risk factor about how =
their political position is actually bad, will cost them customers, etc.Thi=
s is not new, really; we=E2=80=99ve been talking about it around here since=
 at least 2015, when New York=E2=80=99s attorney general  accused Exxon Mob=
ile Corp. of securities fraud for lobbying against action on climate change=
, and we=E2=80=99ve been talking about the letters-to-the-SEC version since=
 2016, when Senator Elizabeth Warren  asked the SEC to investigate some bro=
kerages for lobbying against a fiduciary-duty rule. I do not believe that t=
he New York attorney general was concerned about Exxon=E2=80=99s shareholde=
rs, or that Elizabeth Warren was concerned about those brokerages=E2=80=99 =
shareholders, or that these senators are concerned about Unilever=E2=80=99s=
 shareholders. I believe that the shareholders are a useful pretext for the=
 government to try to punish political speech.This seems bad! To its credit=
,=C2=A0the SEC seems to=C2=A0ignore=C2=A0these letters. Still!
