      SPAC SPAC SPAC
   =20
 =20
The way a special purpose acquisition company works is that a sponsor raise=
s some money from public investors, puts it in a pot, and has two years to =
find a private company to merge with the pot and go public. If the sponsor =
finds a target private company and agrees on a merger, then the public shar=
eholders of the SPAC get to decide to (1) get their money back or (2) get s=
hares in the newly public target company. If they all decide to take their =
money back then usually=C2=A0the deal is off,[1] the SPAC fails, and the sp=
onsor is out of pocket for the startup costs and legal fees of the SPAC. If=
 they mostly decide to take shares in the new company, then the merger clos=
es and the SPAC=E2=80=99s sponsor gets a gigantic fee, in the form of (usua=
lly) shares of the company worth 25% of what the SPAC raised.[2]The result =
of this is that, if you are a SPAC sponsor, you have enormous incentives to=
 do=C2=A0a deal, even if it is not a good deal for the investors in your SP=
AC. If you raise a $1 billion SPAC, sign a deal, and it goes through, then =
your SPAC=E2=80=99s shareholders will end up with $1 billion of stock in th=
e target company and you=E2=80=99ll end up with $250 million of stock. If t=
he stock then falls by 40% because the company is bad and the deal is a dis=
aster, the shareholders will end up with $600 million worth of stock for th=
eir $1 billion investment, a 40% loss, but=C2=A0you=E2=80=99ll=C2=A0end up =
with $150 million, which is much, much better than zero.There are ways to m=
itigate this conflict of interest; some SPAC sponsors lock up their shares =
for a while, or forfeit some of their shares if the stock trades down, or=
=C2=A0invest some of their own money at the deal price, or there are other =
structural features to align incentives. But the main one is just the norma=
l SPAC mechanism of redemption rights: If the SPAC sponsor signs up a deal =
that is bad, the shareholders of the SPAC can take their money back instead=
 of doing the deal, and the deal will fail. So the sponsor has an incentive=
 to do a good deal, because the shareholders are not idiots and won=E2=80=
=99t agree to a bad one.Alternatively, though, the sponsor has an incentive=
 to=C2=A0lie about the deal=C2=A0to the shareholders. Like, the target comp=
any wants to go public and raise money, so it will say =E2=80=9Cwe are a gr=
eat company and everything is good.=E2=80=9D The SPAC sponsor, who does the=
 due diligence and negotiates the deal and then markets it to the sharehold=
ers, wants its cut, so the sponsor will say =E2=80=9Cthis is a great compan=
y and everything is good.=E2=80=9D There are limits on this =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
you need audited financial statements,=C2=A0you=E2=80=99ll get in trouble i=
f you do fraud, repeat sponsors have long-term reputational incentives,=C2=
=A0etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but certainly the sponsor has=C2=A0incentives=C2=A0t=
o make the deal sound better than it is, because the sponsor=E2=80=99s comp=
ensation is based=C2=A0so much=C2=A0more on the deal going through than on =
it being good in the long run.=C2=A0Anyway. In 2020, former Citigroup Inc. =
banker and well-known SPAC sponsor Michael Klein raised a $1.1 billion SPAC=
 called Churchill Capital Corp. III. Churchill III (he=E2=80=99s up to VII =
now) found a merger partner in MultiPlan Inc., which makes software for hea=
lth insurers. Churchill III and MultiPlan put out a proxy statement to mark=
et the deal to the SPAC shareholders, and about 92% of Churchill III=E2=80=
=99s public shareholders decided to roll into MultiPlan; the other 8% took =
back their money, which came to $10.04=C2=A0per share. The merger closed on=
 Oct. 8, 2020. The day before that, Churchill III=E2=80=99s stock closed at=
 $10.25 per share, suggesting that investors expected MultiPlan to be worth=
 a bit more than their $10.04 in cash; the day after, it closed at $9.84, o=
ops.Then things got worse. MultiPlan=E2=80=99s largest customer was UnitedH=
ealth Group Inc. At the time of the SPAC merger, UnitedHealth was working o=
n an in-house software platform called Naviguard, which would replace Multi=
Plan=E2=80=99s software. It is not clear that MultiPlan=E2=80=99s sharehold=
ers realized this[3]:The Proxy disclosed that MultiPlan was dependent on a =
single customer=E2=80=94its largest=E2=80=94for 35% of its revenues.60 It d=
id not disclose that the customer was UnitedHealth Group Inc. (=E2=80=9CUHC=
=E2=80=9D) or that UHC intended to create an in-house data analytics platfo=
rm called Naviguard. Naviguard would allegedly both compete with MultiPlan =
and cause UHC =E2=80=9Cto move all of its key accounts from MultiPlan to Na=
viguard by the end of 2022.=E2=80=9D UHC had publicly discussed its plan fo=
r Naviguard by June 2020.But by November 2020, a month after the merger clo=
sed, they did:On November 11, 2020, an equity research firm published a rep=
ort about MultiPlan discussing, among other things, UHC=E2=80=99s formation=
 of Naviguard.=C2=A0Public MultiPlan=E2=80=99s stock fell to a then-closing=
 low of $6.27 the following day.The stock closed at $4.15 yesterday.=C2=A0Y=
ou can tell a pretty straightforward story there that is like =E2=80=9Cthe =
sponsors of Churchill Capital III really wanted to get a deal done, because=
 there were hundreds of millions of dollars in it for them, so they signed =
up this deal and neglected to mention that MultiPlan was about to lose its =
biggest customer, so shareholders approved the deal and rolled their money =
into the new company, and then the shareholders found out and the stock cra=
tered, but the sponsors still got their payday.=E2=80=9DAnd that is in fact=
 the story that some Churchill/MultiPlan shareholders told, and they sued t=
he sponsors and directors of Churchill. The sponsors and directors asked a =
Delaware court to dismiss the lawsuit on technical grounds of Delaware law =
that I will lazily summarize as =E2=80=9Cit is quite hard to get a Delaware=
 court to hold directors and officers of a company personally responsible f=
or doing a bad acquisition.=E2=80=9D[4] If the board of directors of a comp=
any=C2=A0sells=C2=A0it, and shareholders have complaints, Delaware courts w=
ill hear them out; if the board of a company=C2=A0buys=C2=A0another company=
 and shareholders are mad, that=E2=80=99s harder. (Not impossible! Harder.)=
 Technically in a SPAC deal the SPAC is acquiring the target company and so=
, the Churchill insiders argued, they should not have to face this lawsuit.=
On Monday, though, they lost this argument; Delaware Vice Chancellor Lori W=
ill  allowed the case to go forward. Here is her opinion, which centers on =
the shareholders=E2=80=99 redemption rights. It=E2=80=99s not just that Chu=
rchill allegedly agreed to do a bad deal; it=E2=80=99s that Churchill alleg=
edly impaired the shareholders=E2=80=99 right to redeem, by not telling the=
m everything they=E2=80=99d need to know, because of alleged conflicts of i=
nterest:Viewing the Complaint in the light most favorable to the plaintiffs=
, the crux of the plaintiffs=E2=80=99 claims is that the defendants=E2=80=
=99 actions=E2=80=94principally in the form of misstatements and omissions=
=E2=80=94impaired Churchill public stockholders=E2=80=99 their redemption r=
ights to the defendants=E2=80=99 benefit.=C2=A0In a value-decreasing merger=
, non-redemptions would be valuable to those holding founder shares. Becaus=
e the public stockholders were allegedly not fully informed of all material=
 information about MultiPlan, they exchanged their right to $10.04 per shar=
e=E2=80=94held in a trust for their benefit=E2=80=94for an interest in Publ=
ic MultiPlan.And here is how Vice Chancellor Will describes the conflict:Bo=
th the Class B shares and the Private Placement Warrants held by the Sponso=
r would be worthless if Churchill did not complete a deal.=C2=A0As of the r=
ecord date, the Private Placement=C2=A0Warrants were worth roughly $51 mill=
ion and the founder shares were worth approximately $305 million, represent=
ing a 1,219,900% gain on the Sponsor=E2=80=99s $25,000 investment.=C2=A0The=
se figures would have dropped to zero absent a deal.That is, Klein put up $=
25,000 of startup costs to form the SPAC, and got stock and warrants worth =
about $350 million,=C2=A0if it closed a deal.Churchill=E2=80=99s public sto=
ckholders, on the other hand, would have received $10.04 per share if Churc=
hill had failed to consummate a merger and liquidated. Instead, those that =
did not redeem received Public MultiPlan shares that were allegedly worth l=
ess.In brief, the merger had a value=E2=80=94sufficient to eschew redemptio=
n=E2=80=94to common stockholders if shares of the post-merger entity were w=
orth $10.04. For Klein, given the (non-)value of his stock and warrants if =
no business combination resulted, the merger was valuable well below $10.04=
.=C2=A0So he would happily do a deal worth $8 or $6 or $4, which would stil=
l be worth millions to him, even though it would be a loss to public shareh=
olders. But he=E2=80=99d have to convince shareholders to support that deal=
. And =E2=80=94=C2=A0the plaintiffs allege, and will now get to try to prov=
e=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0he did that by misleading them.=C2=A0There are a coup=
le of interesting defenses here. One is that Klein, as is now fairly common=
 for SPAC sponsors, did structural things to try to mitigate the conflict o=
f interest. For instance he agreed to surrender a portion of his sponsor sh=
ares, and only get them back if the deal traded well (above $12.50 per shar=
e at least a year after the merger). And=C2=A0even the un-surrendered share=
s would be locked up for 18 months, meaning that he=E2=80=99d lose money if=
 the deal traded poorly. You can (and Klein=E2=80=99s lawyers did) point to=
 this stuff and say that his incentives were aligned with the shareholders=
=E2=80=99, and that he=E2=80=99d do much better if the deal went well than =
if it went poorly. The judge didn=E2=80=99t buy it:The defendants assert th=
at the founder shares=E2=80=99 lock-up and the =E2=80=9Cunvestment=E2=80=9D=
 of 45% of the founder shares undercut the plaintiffs=E2=80=99 claim that K=
lein was interested or received a windfall from doing =E2=80=9Cany=E2=80=9D=
 deal.=C2=A0Although the lock-up and =E2=80=9Cunvestment=E2=80=9D lowered t=
he value of the alleged windfall that the defendants received, I cannot con=
clude on a motion to dismiss that it would negate it. Klein held 20,710,281=
 founder shares. Even the vested 55% of those shares, if hypothetically val=
ued at $5 and discounted back 18 months at an aggressive 20% per year, are =
worth more than $40 million dollars.=C2=A0A good deal would be (much)=C2=A0=
more=C2=A0valuable to Klein than a bad deal, but the point here is that a b=
ad deal would still be much more valuable than no deal. So incentives were =
not really aligned.One other defense is: This is just SPACs, man. The judge=
 also did not buy that:The defendants further contend that the Sponsor=E2=
=80=99s promote (in the form of founder shares) cannot trigger entire fairn=
ess because this =E2=80=9Cstructural feature=E2=80=9D would appear in =E2=
=80=9Cany de-SPAC transaction=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cwas not unique to the [=
a]cquisition.=E2=80=9D That this structure has been utilized by other SPACs=
 does not cure it of conflicts.=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know exactly what this=
 means for SPACs. One thing that it means is that if a SPAC does a deal and=
 then the stock goes down, shareholders can sue in Delaware court claiming =
that they were misinformed about the problems with the deal. But they proba=
bly could have sued anyway =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Ceverything is securities=
 fraud,=E2=80=9D after all, and surely=C2=A0omitting important information =
in a SPAC merger proxy is a thing =E2=80=94=C2=A0so I=E2=80=99m not sure ho=
w much it matters that they can sue for fiduciary-duty breaches as well as =
securities fraud.What is perhaps more important here is just the general se=
nse from a Delaware court that SPAC deals are=C2=A0inherently=C2=A0conflict=
ed, that the basic structure is built around conflicts of interest and that=
 any SPAC deal that ends up in court will be treated with suspicion.=C2=A0
