      Elsewhere in SPACs
   =20
 =20
You know who sponsored a SPAC but=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0push to get a de=
al done=C2=A0at any cost? Colin Kaepernick. This is from last month but:The=
 Change Co. seemed like the perfect company for Colin Kaepernick=E2=80=99s =
SPAC to buy. The California lender focuses on minority borrowers underserve=
d by traditional banks, a snug fit with the former National Football League=
 star=E2=80=99s social-justice activism.But a deal ran aground last week ov=
er a peculiar issue: Mr. Kaepernick=E2=80=99s reluctance to stump for the m=
erger on live television, people familiar with the matter said.Mr. Kaeperni=
ck balked at requests from Change Co. executives that he sit for an appeara=
nce with George Stephanopoulos on =E2=80=9CGood Morning America=E2=80=9D an=
d declined to participate in interviews as part of the rollout, according t=
o an internal document.The deal is now dead, these people said.You could ha=
ve a model here that is like =E2=80=9Cthe long-term brand value to Colin Ka=
epernick of=C2=A0not=C2=A0shilling for a SPAC on =E2=80=98Good Morning Amer=
ica=E2=80=99 outweighs the short-term value that he could get from his spon=
sor shares in this SPAC.=E2=80=9D Which was not trivial:The sponsor group, =
Messrs. Kaepernick and Najafi, were set to contribute $10 million. Had the =
deal been completed, they would have received founder shares in the combine=
d company worth about $80 million, according to the SPAC=E2=80=99s public f=
ilings. Mr. Kaepernick and the sponsor group also were going to donate up t=
o one million shares, with a value near $10 million, to down-payment assist=
ance efforts to support Black homeownership.But you could have the same mod=
el for Michael Klein! Much more so! The guy has done VII SPACs so far; a go=
od reputation for doing good SPAC deals is way more valuable to him in the =
long run than it is to Colin Kaepernick.[5] Long-term reputational concerns=
=C2=A0can=C2=A0outweigh a SPAC sponsor=E2=80=99s incentives to get a deal d=
one, is the lesson of Colin Kaepernick=E2=80=99s SPAC, I guess.
