      NFT Stuff: Other
   =20
 =20
Yesterday in =E2=80=9CThings Happen=E2=80=9D I included a link to a New Yor=
k Post story titled =E2=80=9C=E2=80=9890 Day Fianc=C3=A9=E2=80=99 star reti=
res from selling farts after heart attack scare=E2=80=9D because, you know,=
 perfect headline. But what I missed is that after retiring from selling fa=
rts in jars, the =E2=80=9C90 Day Fianc=C3=A9=E2=80=9D star has moved on to =
selling, you know what it is, I=E2=80=99m sorry, I=E2=80=99m sorry, but:=C2=
=A0She=E2=80=99s still going to sell her farts as non-fungible tokens, more=
 commonly known as NFTs. ...But while Matto has semi-retired from the real-=
world fart jar business, she=E2=80=99s still pursuing the world of NFTs, wh=
ere she sells cartoon images of her fart jars. Non-fungible tokens are most=
 often associated with jpeg images, but they=E2=80=99re essentially a decen=
tralized receipt on the blockchain that can be any kind of hyperlink.I=E2=
=80=99m truly, truly sorry; nobody wants to be talking about this less than=
 I do but sometimes when you write a financial newsletter you have unpleasa=
nt responsibilities.=C2=A0In general my view is that a non-fungible token =
=E2=80=9Cof,=E2=80=9D for instance, a painting is much worse than the actua=
l painting, because I=E2=80=99d rather have a painting on my wall than one =
on the blockchain. But I suppose an NFT fart might be better than an actual=
 one? Like, if you have a negative-utility good, why not sell an NFT of it =
instead of the thing itself?
