<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">SPAC SPAC SPAC</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way a special purpose acquisition =
company works is that a sponsor raises some money from public investors, pu=
ts it in a pot, and has two years to find a private company to merge with t=
he pot and go public. If the sponsor finds a target private company and agr=
ees on a merger, then the public shareholders of the SPAC get to decide to =
(1) get their money back or (2) get shares in the newly public target compa=
ny. If they all decide to take their money back then <em>usually=C2=A0</em>=
the deal is off,[1] the SPAC fails, and the sponsor is out of pocket for th=
e startup costs and legal fees of the SPAC. If they mostly decide to take s=
hares in the new company, then the merger closes and the SPAC=E2=80=99s spo=
nsor gets a gigantic fee, in the form of (usually) shares of the company wo=
rth 25% of what the SPAC raised.[2]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The res=
ult of this is that, if you are a SPAC sponsor, you have enormous incentive=
s to do=C2=A0<em>a deal</em>, even if it is not a good deal for the investo=
rs in your SPAC. If you raise a $1 billion SPAC, sign a deal, and it goes t=
hrough, then your SPAC=E2=80=99s shareholders will end up with $1 billion o=
f stock in the target company and you=E2=80=99ll end up with $250 million o=
f stock. If the stock then falls by 40% because the company is bad and the =
deal is a disaster, the shareholders will end up with $600 million worth of=
 stock for their $1 billion investment, a 40% loss, but=C2=A0<em>you=E2=80=
=99ll=C2=A0</em>end up with $150 million, which is much, much better than z=
ero.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are ways to mitigate this confli=
ct of interest; some SPAC sponsors lock up their shares for a while, or for=
feit some of their shares if the stock trades down, or=C2=A0invest some of =
their own money at the deal price, or there are other structural features t=
o align incentives. But the main one is just the normal SPAC mechanism of r=
edemption rights: If the SPAC sponsor signs up a deal that is bad, the shar=
eholders of the SPAC can take their money back instead of doing the deal, a=
nd the deal will fail. So the sponsor has an incentive to do a good deal, b=
ecause the shareholders are not idiots and won=E2=80=99t agree to a bad one=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Alternatively, though, the sponsor has an=
 incentive to=C2=A0<em>lie about the deal</em>=C2=A0to the shareholders. Li=
ke, the target company wants to go public and raise money, so it will say =
=E2=80=9Cwe are a great company and everything is good.=E2=80=9D The SPAC s=
ponsor, who does the due diligence and negotiates the deal and then markets=
 it to the shareholders, wants its cut, so the sponsor will say =E2=80=9Cth=
is is a great company and everything is good.=E2=80=9D There are limits on =
this =E2=80=94=C2=A0you need audited financial statements,=C2=A0you=E2=80=
=99ll get in trouble if you do fraud, repeat sponsors have long-term reputa=
tional incentives,=C2=A0etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but certainly the sponsor has=
=C2=A0<em>incentives=C2=A0</em>to make the deal sound better than it is, be=
cause the sponsor=E2=80=99s compensation is based=C2=A0<em>so much=C2=A0</e=
m>more on the deal going through than on it being good in the long run.=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway. In 2020, former Citigroup Inc. =
banker and well-known SPAC sponsor Michael Klein <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26278571.277651/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9B=
cmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE3OTMyMjkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIwMDIyMDM2L3R2NTM4MjA3XzQ=
yNGI0Lmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB70fec0f3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">raised a $1.1 billio=
n SPAC</a> called Churchill Capital Corp. III. Churchill III (he=E2=80=99s =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26278571.277651/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9jZ2ktYmluL2Jyb3dzZS1lZGdhcj9hY3Rpb249Z2V0Y29tcGFue=
SZDSUs9MDAwMTgyODI0OCZvd25lcj1pbmNsdWRlJmNvdW50PTQwJmhpZGVmaWxpbmdzPTA/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7d7939df" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">up to VII</a> now) found a merger pa=
rtner in MultiPlan Inc., which makes software for health insurers. Churchil=
l III and MultiPlan put out a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/26278571.277651/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9=
kYXRhLzE3OTMyMjkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIwMTA2MjQ1L3RtMjAyNTI1OC01X2RlZm0xNGEuaHRt/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB201a2acc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">proxy statement</a> to market the=
 deal to the SPAC shareholders, and about 92% of Churchill III=E2=80=99s pu=
blic shareholders decided to roll into MultiPlan; the other 8% <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26278571.277651/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE3OTMyMjkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIwMTEzNjIwL=
3RtMjAzMTMyNWQxXzhrLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB72b7cdc4" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">took b=
ack their money</a>, which came to $10.04=C2=A0per share. The merger closed=
 on Oct. 8, 2020. The day before that, Churchill III=E2=80=99s stock closed=
 at $10.25 per share, suggesting that investors expected MultiPlan to be wo=
rth a bit more than their $10.04 in cash; the day after, it closed at $9.84=
, oops.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Then things got worse. MultiPlan=E2=
=80=99s largest customer was UnitedHealth Group Inc. At the time of the SPA=
C merger, UnitedHealth was working on an in-house software platform called =
Naviguard, which would replace MultiPlan=E2=80=99s software. It is not clea=
r that MultiPlan=E2=80=99s shareholders realized this[3]:</p><blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Proxy disclosed that MultiPlan was dependent=
 on a single customer=E2=80=94its largest=E2=80=94for 35% of its revenues.6=
0 It did not disclose that the customer was UnitedHealth Group Inc. (=E2=80=
=9CUHC=E2=80=9D) or that UHC intended to create an in-house data analytics =
platform called Naviguard. Naviguard would allegedly both compete with Mult=
iPlan and cause UHC =E2=80=9Cto move all of its key accounts from MultiPlan=
 to Naviguard by the end of 2022.=E2=80=9D UHC had publicly discussed its p=
