es undercut the plaintiffs=E2=80=99 claim that Klein was interested or rece=
ived a windfall from doing =E2=80=9Cany=E2=80=9D deal.=C2=A0Although the lo=
ck-up and =E2=80=9Cunvestment=E2=80=9D lowered the value of the alleged win=
dfall that the defendants received, I cannot conclude on a motion to dismis=
s that it would negate it. Klein held 20,710,281 founder shares. Even the v=
ested 55% of those shares, if hypothetically valued at $5 and discounted ba=
ck 18 months at an aggressive 20% per year, are worth more than $40 million=
 dollars.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A good deal wo=
uld be (much)=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>valuable to Klein than a bad deal, bu=
t the point here is that a bad deal would still be much more valuable than =
no deal. So incentives were not really aligned.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">One other defense is: This is just SPACs, man. The judge also did not =
buy that:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The defendants furthe=
r contend that the Sponsor=E2=80=99s promote (in the form of founder shares=
